    "answer" : "If you're asking about education loan certificate to claim income tax exemption as per section 80E of IT act then simply go to your bank and ask your loan officer to give a Education loan certificate for the current financial year / whichever year you want. If your parents/ guardian is a coborrower for your loan then he/she can also avail the benefits of section 80E for his income tax calculation. Some banks like SBI simply upload these certificate (education/ home loan certificates) in the internet banking profiles of the customers. For these auto generated certificates you don't need hand signature from the bank, these certificates are equally valid.  The above is one such education loan certificate generated from my SBI internet banking profile. However, in case you don't have internet banki Continue Reading I don’t know why students find it taxing to apply for Education Loans and always try to avoid that by emptying the bank balance of parents. Hey generation Z, please don’t do that. Don’t compromise your College or University just for the sake of avoiding an Education Loan. Many students consider Education loans as ‘Debt’. If I can substitute the word ‘Debt’ with ‘Leverage’ that would be great. You can feel negative vibes with the term Debt. I say this because students try to avoid this a lot or they just procrastinate the process of getting it. If they delay the process to acquire an Education Loan then they are left with a compromised loan with Higher Rate of Interest and Lower Sanctioned Amount due to lack of time in hand. Our mind keeps on struggling between the polarities of good and bad Continue Reading Education loan is different type of loan therefore release of installments is also different. Generally educational institutes demand college fees semester wise or year wise. So after admission in a college the next fees is due after the semester/ year ends. Therefore, Banks require following documents for release of next installment:— a) Demand letter of the college / University b) Mark sheet of the student which shows that he/she has cleared the last exam c) Receipt / acknowledgement of the last amount paid to the college/ University d) Bill / demand letter of hostel fees / mess fees/ books etc. etc. The student shall have to deposit margin amount (Student contribution) If any and then the Bank remits the demand amount of fees directly to the college / university",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:07:36.105Z"),
    "question" : "Can a student in India get education loan on himself? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
