    "answer" : "It varies so widely so the average is not necessarily indicative of your situation. Also, physicians today did not take out the same amount during their time in medical school. Tuition has gone through the roof relative to inflation! It doesn’t make sense to base it solely on their experience, so nobody knows for sure. I paid off all my undergraduate loans and my parent’s mortgage with my prior business. I plan to repay my medical student loans by graduation or 1 year into residency with my current business. However, I also went to school in Texas, one of the lowest in tuition, so my situation is not the norm. My yearly tuition is only 17k. The national average for state schools is around 35k a year, not including cost of living. I don’t have to pay rent so my cost of living is very very lo Continue Reading This is a nebulous question.  The question revolves around how much money was borrowed, whether interest accrued during medical school (and if so at what rate?) and when repayment must begin.  State medical schools have lower tuition rates than private medical schools.  Parents may pay some or all or there may be financial aid in the form of grants.   Residencies vary in pay levels while a resident and once out of residency pay levels between different specialties vary.   If a student has to borrow everything and goes to a private school it may be very difficult.  In my situation, I attended my state medical school (tuition 30 yrs ago $2500 but is now $29,000 for an in state student) and exited residency with a total of $17,500 debt.  I paid it off in in 5 months. Tuition rates for undergradu Continue Reading",
