{
    "_id" : ObjectId("60373f680c817f0398fb77a1"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/Is-Union-Bank-good-for-an-education-loan?-",
    "answer" : "Education loan is applied by almost all students aspiring to go different countries to do their Masters. Let me explain the process and struggle I faced during this COVID situation to get my education loan sanctioned. After getting the offer letter from Saint Mary’s University, Halifax, Canada for my Masters in Data Analytics & Computing, I was filled with joy and also thought about rest of the process to get my Visa done. I started searching for banks from March 2020 with lesser rate of interest ( which I think is important) and have gone through bank portals of almost all banks in India. What I could find is except 3 to 4 small banks, every bank has the loan margin amount which I needed. I initially thought of HDFC Credila and ICICI as well, but seeing their RoI, I was in a dilemma of going to it or not. I know if I did go through anyone of them, by this time I would have Visa in my hand. But, as my University postponed the course to January 2021, I thought I had so much of time to search other banks as well. Then came to my mind is Bank of Baroda with lesser rate of interest. I went to the nearest branch of BoB and asked the process of applying education loan in that bank ( I actually went through the bank loan portal and all things on my own by that time). The process was very clear and the documents which you need to submit will be handy if you have a flat/house to keep as collateral. I filled the application form and submitted all the documents to the bank. The process was quite fast and within less time, legal opinion by advocate and legal valuation of the property is done. While I was waiting for Mortgage registration process, one day I got a call from BoB saying that my loan got cancelled as Pre-Visa disbursement is not happening in COVID time for non-premier institutes of BoB. This was a big shock to me and I couldn’t come out of that for 1 week. The thought of re-applying in other bank with lesser RoI and the process is tough. One of my friends in same cohort of SMU (Hem Sai Charan) suggested me to talk with WeMakeScholars once on this issue. Then I immediately approached them in no time and explained everything that happened to me with Bank of Baroda. Meanwhile as I got news that SMU is conducting online classes in January, I deferred my admission to September 2021 as I am LASIK operated. I need to thank Ms. Prathyusha from WeMakeScholars in understanding my issue and solving the problem. After WeMakeScholars and BoB talked on this issue, they asked me one thing. The assurance from University that, if Visa gets cancelled then the money paid to University need to be returned from University, which luckily I got it from SMU. I submitted the assurance and again re-applied the loan from Bank of Baroda via WeMakeScholars this time. This time the process was much smoother as already legal opinion and legal valuation is already done. I also need to thank Durga and Anand from Bank of Baroda SMS team, in processing my documents and the process. Due to the COVID time, the process was somewhat slow but Bank of Baroda is such a good bank to apply loans. Two days back, I got my Loan Sanction Letter and I am looking forward for disbursement and Visa process. The best bank really depends on your situation and varies person to person. You should evaluate the banks offers on these metrics to identify what works best for your case Interest Rate: This is the obvious feature many students compare. Pls note that the below factors are sometimes equally important.EMI payment before graduation: Banks usually provide a moratorium period up to 1 year after graduation during which the student can secure a job and start making payments towards his loan. Terms of the loan like interest rate also differ from bank to bank during moratorium.Early repayment penalty: Many banks charge an early repayment penalty if you want to pay your loan back early. Please make sure you understand the terms involved and compare the same across banks.Loan processing fee: Most banks charge a one-time fee to process your loan which is added to the total principal amount. Make sure you compare the loan processing fee along with the interest rate.Depending on your requirements, here are a few options to choose from: Vidyalakshmi: The NSDL launched vidyalakshmi.co.in to help students in searching for and applying for the best education loans. Vidyalakshmi works with all 40 major banks such as SBI, IDBI, BOI, Andhra Bank, etc. Please note that Vidyalakshmi mostly works with the public banks and does not help you compare your options among private banks, NBFC’s, and the new fintech startups.Public Banks / PSU’s: Usually, public banks like SBI and Bank of Baroda offer the best rates. However, they also have the most arduous process for application. If you or your parents have a personal relationship with the bank manager at a PSU, this is a good option to consider.Private Banks: Private banks like Axis and Kotak offer bank loans at reasonable interest rates and quick turn-around times.NBFC’s: HDFC Credila and Avanse offer some of the most flexible loan terms. They usually offer the biggest loan amounts and have options that do not include collateral. However, their interest rates are higher than banksFintech companies: Prodigy Finance and MPower Financing are 2 fintech startups that offer all their loans without collateral. They also offer a fully online process to apply for loans, and offer very aggressive interest rates.Good luck with your education! Yes, you can definitely avail two education loans from separate banks at the same time.People may face financial crunch or may need money for higher education. This is the situation when banks and NBFCs come into consideration. You can apply personal loan for a higher education from one bank and at the same time a personal loan from another bank.  You can also apply for personal loans from multiple banks for different purposes.",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:10:48.500Z"),
    "question" : "Is Union Bank good for an education loan? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

