    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/Is-a-good-CIBIL-score-a-must-for-taking-an-education-loan?-",
    "answer" : "Not many people, not even experts, will tell you what I'm going to tell you now. I watched my CIBIL score go from 870 to 619 for bad repayment and then shooted up to 812 in 4 months. I'll be happy to give you some tips. 1. Your CIBIL score is updated on a monthly basis by your bank (every month end) 2. Salary getting credited every month adds 5-10 pts to your score 3. Transaction of 1,00,000 to 2,00,000 every month in your salary bank account adds an extra 15-20 pts to your score 4. Getting loan against gold or any property and repaying it on time every month improves your score by 20-25 pts. But a single cheque bounce will eat 25-30 pts of your score, so be careful. 5. You'll get a bonus of 3-5 pts for every cheque cleared successfully without bounce. It can be cheque to pay your emi or a cheq Continue Reading Thanks for A2A. Yes, you can! You can improve your CIBIL score before you apply for the loan as it will reduce your chances of rejection. Refer to this blog for help - Prep for your Education Loan for MS/MBA Abroad: CIBIL Score. Some tips to improve your CIBIL score - Always pay your dues on time. If you have taken a loan, repay on time to avoid default. Late payments are viewed negatively by the lender.Keep your credit balance low. Do not take more credit than you can afford to repay.Keep a healthy mix of credit. Do not take necessary unsecured loans as it is also viewed negatively by the lender.Review your credit history frequently.A CIBIL score of more than 700 is accepted by lenders as above average and is considered a good score. Also, refer to How to Get an Education Loan with a Low CIBIL Continue Reading Though you'll face some problems initially while trying to obtain an education loan or a Personal Loan for higher education with that CIBIL score. However, with some research, you'll find a lender offering the required credit scheme to people with CIBIL score less than 750. See, CIBIL score is important, especially if the credit scheme you are planning to take is unsecured in nature. However, it is not the only criteria that determine the eligibility of an applicant for a loan. The other factors are the monthly income of the person, the debt-burden ratio, the loan eligibility of the person, and the repayment capacity of the person etc. Let's say a person earns around 50k a month and can pay up to 30k as EMI every month, he/she is absolutely eligible for a loan even if their CIBIL score is le Continue Reading",
