{
    "_id" : ObjectId("603740530c817f0398fb7a9f"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/Which-education-loan-is-affordable-for-MBA-studies-in-India?-",
    "answer" : "Germany has a decent job requirement for students skilled in Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics, collectively known as STEM courses. Pursuing one such course is a very good option, and can be supplemented by doing a Master’s in order to strengthen the job prospects there. Automation and technology are two fields in which Germany is among the global leaders.  It is important to know that most courses in Germany require a very low to no tuition fee, making Germany one of the preferred countries for pursuing undergraduate courses outside of India. (Here is the list of courses available). There are also a number of scholarships for Indian students, made available by DAAD. As the tuition fee there is low, the major expense that one would incur is the cost of living. On average, the monthly expense can be around 700-800 Euros (including accommodation, food, travel etc.) The duration of the undergraduate program in Germany is generally 3 years. So, the total living cost could be around 30,000 Euros, which when converted using the conversion rate of 1 Euro= Rs 76, comes close to Rs 23 L. Adding another 2 L for miscellaneous expenses, brings the figure close to Rs 25 L. Hence, when compared to countries like USA, where undergraduate studies can cost over Rs 1 Cr in several universities, Germany is a much safer, reasonable and more recommended option. Here is the process for obtaining a Permanent Residency in Germany after your education there. There are several banks in India that offer secured education loans for studying in Germany. SBI runs a scheme called the SBI Global Ed-Vantage scheme to provide loans for studies outside India. Other banks like Bank of Baroda also provide attractive deals on education loans. Alternatively, you may approach GyanDhan, which is an education loan startup by IIT alumni working closely with leading banks across the country to make the education loan process extremely convenient for the student. GyanDhan does not charge any kind of a fee! Good luck! Definitely not from banks. However, there are a few organizations that offer interest-free loans if you are interested in pursuing higher education. K. C. Mahindra Education Trust and Narotam Sekhsaria Foundation are two such organizations which offer interest-free loans for pursuing a postgraduate degree from foreign universities. As you might have already guessed, these scholarships are highly competitive and require a lot of hard work. Check out these articles if you want more tips on what these scholarships are, and what you need to do to apply for them. There might be several other similar organizations that you can research about. Apart from these scholarships and grants, some colleges also have alumni associations that support their students by providing low or zero-interest loans to help fund their postgraduate degrees. Talk to your college’s alumni association to see if they have any such provisions. As per IBA Model Policy [1] , the following expenses shall be considered for Education Loans: Fee payable to college/ school/ hostelExamination/ Library/ Laboratory feeTravel expenses/ passage money for studies abroadInsurance premium for student borrower, if applicable (Insurance become optional after CGFSEL[2] )Caution deposit, Building fund / refundable deposit supported by Institution bills/receipts. **Purchase of books/ equipment/ instruments/ uniforms***Purchase of computer at reasonable cost, if required for completion of the course***Any other expense required to complete the course - like study tours, project work, thesis, etc.***Notes: * Reasonable lodging and boarding charges will be considered in case the student chooses / is required to opt for outside accommodation. ** These expenses could be considered subject to the condition that the amount does not exceed 10% of the total tuition fees for the entire course. *** It is likely that expenditure under Item Nos. 6, 7 & 8 above may not be available in the schedule of fees and charges prescribed by the college authorities. Therefore, a realistic assessment may be made of the requirement under these heads. However, the maximum expenses included under 6, 7 & 8 may be capped at 20% of the total tuition fees payable for completion of the course. For example, if your total tuition fees for completing the course is Rs. 4.00 lacs, then these expenses put together shall only be considered to a maximum of Rs. 80,000/- Footnotes[1] https://www.iba.org.in/pdf/education/Model_Edu_loan.pdf[2] Credit Guarantee Fund Scheme for Education Loans",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:14:43.985Z"),
    "question" : "Which education loan is affordable for MBA studies in India? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

