{
    "_id" : ObjectId("6037434f0c817f0398fb84a2"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/Is-any-collateral-needed-to-get-an-education-loan-for-an-MBA-from-IIM?-",
    "answer" : "In terms of return on investment many of the non IIMs like FMS,SP Jain,XLRI,MDI,IIFT,JBIMS,NMIMS etc are much better than the new IIMs and a couple of old IIMs Almost all colleges in top 30 have a total fees of around 12 lakh plus and hence taking an education loan makes a lot of sense Now for a loan of say 15lakhs your EMI would be 32,241 per month at the interest of 10.5% per annum payable for 5 years or 25,291 per month for 7 years . For the two years you study your dad would be paying an interest of 13,125 per month.Or  your emi would be 39,205 per month at the interest of 10.5% per annum payable for 5 years or 30,754 per month for 7 years if no one pays any interest while you are studying. So in any case you should be in a position to keep aside 25 to 30k post your MBA for repayment. With an average salary of 9.22 lakhs you can expect an in hand salary of 60-65k in which you can comfortably pay off the EMIs Now lets talk about entrepreneurship. While doing my MBA ,I was lucky to be surrounded by a lot of people bitten by the startup bug. Many of them,including my very close friends started of various forms of ventures in the college itself, right from an eCommerce platform for ladies handbag, to a cab aggregator with allied services in Mumbai.  But all of them were mature enough to sit for the final placement and bag a job because they knew that they were not profitable and wont be in the near forseable future, also they are in the experimentation mode trying their hands on various things,learning the real life challenges, challenges you wont find in books and case studies but when you set out to get things moving. They are willing to fail but learn and ultimately come up with a model that works, and all of this is going to take time,which they will make from their busy schedules once they start working in the corporate world and if their passion lives on The idea is that you don't start a venture just from scratch with out a backup plan and a support system, it takes time and a lot of patience and effort, and its far from being as easy and straight forward as hype around startups would want you to believe. So my advice is join the college, and also side by side work on your ideas. Get a job to pay off your expenses and EMI and also work on your startup to make the product really good. Save a little that will be your starting operational expense till you reach a point that you think you can now pitch for and get a funding. Once you get your seed fund quit the corporate job and keep paying the EMI from the salary you would be drawing from your own company. Yes, plot can be kept as a collateral security with bank. Some banks provide 70% of the government valuation and others provide 100% of it. Plots must have a boundary wall, as any bank would not prefer open land or plots. You must have the complete documents of the collateral, including approved plan, registered sale deed, mutation, completion certificate in case of construction etc. Plots must be registered under Municipal corporation as banks do not accept collateral which are under Gram Panchayat or unauthorised colonies. If the market value of the Plot is INR 50 Lakhs, for instance, then it gets evaluated by the appointed civil engineers and valuers, who quote and produce valuation reports according to the current rates of that area, which is always less than the market value. So, if the market value is INR 50 Lakhs, and government value came to be INR 40 Lakhs, the bank will provide 70% of that value; however, some banks provide 100% of the value. Most of the banks have margin money criteria, but some banks do not ask for that, if the admission is secured in a renowned university. Students are not fully aware of these terms, and always suffer while finding out what is best for them. This problem has been eradicated completely, since Gyandhan came into the market. Our main objective is to help students get admission into their dream college, and at the same time, funding it, by evaluating their profiles and initiating the suitable education loan process. Interesting and amazing fact is that all this is for free. We have a highly professional loan counseling team that evaluates your overall profile and starts the loan process with the best possible bank or lender. Unlike any other consultants, there are no hidden costs and the reason behind this is that we have corporate tie-ups with Public sector banks like SBI, Bank of Baroda, Axis bank etc. and we get our revenue from them. We are helping students in every possible way and figuring out options for those who do not have any security to keep as collateral but have a dream to study abroad and secure their futures. If you're one among them, check your loan eligibility or request a call back. First, let's have a look at the average, minimum, and maximum salaries offered across campuses in the previous Academic Year (Figures for this year would be higher since placements have improved this season)Salary packages offered in Top B-schools like IIMs, XLRI, etc. Assuming that you get the college which offered the minimum amongst the lowest packages in your graduating year (IIM K with 6 lacs in this example- the college can change from year to year, and so can the package). Assuming, further, that you stay at Delhi/Mumbai and have monthly expenses of around ~20-22k (Obviously, if you have got the lowest package, you would have to try and bring down that figure as low as possible). I personally have an average package(11lpa), and I keep my expenses below 20,000 per month. 6 lacs would amount to, typically: 40,000 in-hand per month. So, even if you consider the option that you won't save much in the first 1-2 years, you can still start off with an EMI amount of about 20,000 pm to begin with.This translates to a period of about 10 years.  However, always keep in mind that your educational achievements will stay with you and opportunities will be there if you work hard. I know of quite a few people who started with 6.5-7 lacs in their first year but graduated to 10-10.5 lpa jobs within their second year. Once your income increase, the EMI shouldn't be much of a bother. I would suggest, for CTCs upto 14 lacs, you should keep the loan reimbursement period constant at 6-7 years (you get tax benefits). More than that amount, you can look at decreasing the loan tenure without significantly hampering your lifestyle or your savings. P.S: This is the absolute worst case scenario, considering you get the lowest package possible, you stay in a high-cost-of-living city, etc.",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:27:27.082Z"),
    "question" : "Is any collateral needed to get an education loan for an MBA from IIM? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

