{
    "_id" : ObjectId("6037478a0c817f0398fb92fd"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/What-questions-should-I-ask-from-Prodigy-Finance-before-applying-for-education-loans?-",
    "answer" : "While my collections experience has been in the U.S., I am very familiar with the tactics shown in the video. I am a little curious as to when this video was made, looks like 2009 from I could find. In the U.S., all of those tactics, such as making threats of legal action that cannot or would not be taken, are illegal. The FDCPA, Fair Debt Collections Practices Act, was enacted in 1977, but it did not really start to protect the consumer effectively until 2006–7. I started doing collections in 2004, so I saw the business go through a lot of changes. I found that the U.K. has enacted laws similar to the FDCPA, but as you stated, Prodigy is not a regulated or authorized lender, so they would not be held accountable to such rules. Also, the FDCPA covers collection activities of 3rd parties, like where I worked, not the actual lender. I found this article FinTech: Here's Why MBAs, Investors Are Flocking To Tuition Crowdfunder Prodigy Finance which says that over 99% of loans are repaid, so there is apparently isn’t need for additional oversight. I am a conservative when it comes to government, and this isn’t a situation that warrants the government to intervene. Not only are the borrowers extremely well-versed in finance, clearly aware of the business model, How It Works | Invest In MBA Community-Based Student Loans | Prodigy Finance but the method used to enforce repayment could not be regulated. Prodigy uses social pressure, by publishing a dashboard of individual student repayment activity, which impacts a student’s ability to pursue a career within any business network. This successful business model works for the individuals involved, and government intervention would only result in arbitrary rules set by people less knowledgeable than those involved, unnecessary regulatory costs, that would have unintended consequences, such as a a higher default rate; the government could effectively cripple and put Prodigy and companies like it out of business. That’s not to say that the FDCPA is bad legislation; it lays the legal foundation for consumers to sue when they have been harassed, lied to, or otherwise compelled to pay a debt which puts their families financial security at risk. The FDCPA became necessary because of unethical business practices and lack of consumer knowledge and access to knowledge to make wise decisions. Legislation still has not found a way to have collectors abide by contrary rules that collectors must identify themselves and the nature of the call but avoid disclosure to third parties when leaving voicemail messages. Also, not all consumers can effectively invoke protections, due to the lack of legal assistance at the state level when dealing with businesses located in another jurisdiction. First, the big college question, will this money I spend to get a degree help me make more money over my lifetime than not going to college. The answer is still a firm yes, BUT it won’t always come back in 10 years or less like it used to. Often your return on investment for college comes on a longer time frame in money. I also encourage you to think about your health, working in an office gives you the opportunity to have more control over your health than working a factory line or another labor intensive job(doesn’t mean you’ll take better care of yourself but more of your health is your choice with a degree than without). Next, will I actually complete this degree? Lot of people in the late 90s and early 2000s went to college for two years and dropped out. It cost less back then, so the stakes weren’t so high, but with the rising cost of college tuition and the surrounding costs of lodging/food/entertainment all rising the stakes are much higher now. The only person who can answer that is you, but if you take the need to be present and put forth the effort to pass(no one cares if you got all As and also no one gets all As in college) then you will better yourself long term. Finally, how much should I borrow. Tuition is required, but many student loans offer residual funds and there is a scale for how much you can add onto the base tuition cost for lodging and food. I knew a lot of people who treated that like play money and that’s a huge mistake. I would say only add as much residual debt as you absolutely need. It may be tempting to take that residual money to fix your car or buy a new TV but remember student loan debt must be paid, you cannot bankrupt it and you will never get away from it until it is paid. Please do not add consumer items you can live without to this protected type of debt. Move back to a dorm, get rid of your car and walk to class before you put anything car or consumer related on a student loan. Lastly, how quickly can I get through to a bachelor’s degree? The last statistic I read stated that less than a quarter of people with bachelor’s degrees are working in a field related to their degree. That doesn’t make a degree a bad idea, it just means the labor market and the college campus are not directly in line. However, having a bachelor’s degree is still a requirement for a vast majority of corporate jobs. It tells the hiring department you can do things you don’t want to do because you need to do them. No one wants to get up for Philosophy at 8am. No one! But you had to and you did it and you finished your degree program. That is what having a bachelor’s degree is telling the hiring department and that is the value of having one in something, anything, even if you’re not going to work specifically in your degree field. Know what you’re getting for your money and find the shortest route to a bachelor’s degree that you do not hate. Anything in the business department will translate well to any professional job. Think of it like your cover charge to office work and just get it done. Yes - Prodigy Finance is relatively new and this is far too high an interest rate in any country globally in the current environment of globally low interest rates (or negative EURIBOR interest rates in the Eurozone).  It would be better to avoid such loan funding entirely, or negotiate a substantial fee discount directly with the Business School (often the top tier business schools will subsequently call this a \"scholarship\"; e.g. for €30,000 off their advertised headline MBA tuition fee rate) Details of discounts (scholarships) are Cracks in finances put business schools at risk - FT.com  Alternatively, stick to a conventional bank loan funding source, where the jurisdiction, legal system and ability to negotiate a restructuring or write off of such MBA debt is clear and well defined. Also, make sure any tuition fee payments to the school are paid by a credit card (e.g. Visa, American Express, Mastercard) with consumer protection (rather than paying directly by cash, cheque, bank transfer or debit card), in the event of a dispute later on and needing to pursue a refund or other claim. For example, in the United Kingdom, credit cards have excellent consumer protection under Section 75 of the Consumer Credit Act, in the event that the MBA tuition goods or service prove to be unfit or unsatisfactory. Finally, many countries have credit cards with 0% interest rates on 'new spending' for up to 18 months. This would provide for 0% finance on paying for MBA tuition fees by credit card (e.g. £20,000 of MBA tuition on a 0% interest rate credit card), and be therefore much cheaper than the 10% loan funding offered by Prodigy Finance. In addition, it is possible to subsequently balance transfer the tuition fees on the 0% interest credit card to another 0% interest credit card when closer to the expiration of the 18 month interest free period, for usually only a relatively small 'balance transfer' fee.Another advantage of using a 0% new purchases credit card is the ability to get points, rewards, or other \"cash back\" for the purchase. See http://www.moneysavingexpert.com/credit-cards/best-0-credit-cards",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:45:30.136Z"),
    "question" : "What questions should I ask from Prodigy Finance before applying for education loans? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

