    "_id" : ObjectId("603747b30c817f0398fb93c8"),
    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/Is-it-worth-doing-an-MBBS-in-a-self-finance-college-with-an-education-loan?-",
    "answer" : "I don’t know why students find it taxing to apply for Education Loans and always try to avoid that by emptying the bank balance of parents. Hey generation Z, please don’t do that. Don’t compromise your College or University just for the sake of avoiding an Education Loan. Many students consider Education loans as ‘Debt’. If I can substitute the word ‘Debt’ with ‘Leverage’ that would be great. You can feel negative vibes with the term Debt. I say this because students try to avoid this a lot or they just procrastinate the process of getting it. If they delay the process to acquire an Education Loan then they are left with a compromised loan with Higher Rate of Interest and Lower Sanctioned Amount due to lack of time in hand. Our mind keeps on struggling between the polarities of good and bad between them and thus this leads to disturbance. We often look for reviews about loans and then we make a judgement about a certain type of loan where the certain population goes but in reality it may not be a right fit for you. Leverage, on the other hand, has positive connotations attached to it. Leverage is further termed as “to use something to advantage” or in a financial sense, “to borrow since one can earn better on it.” Don’t you find it convincing? Let me explain to you in these four points: a. Leverage when your appreciation opportunity is high - This means about having job prospects for your Educational course which you intend to pursue. If you are confident about that then you’re good to go ahead. Many students are able to repay off the loans within the first 5 years of the repayment period. b. Leverage should be a choice - Taking a loan is nothing but borrowing from your future earnings to fund your present. So, unless the asset you are borrowing for is earning more than the cost of borrowing, you are leaving your future under-funded. c. Always have a plan for your Education loan - You’ve to breakdown all your expenses related to your living expenses as you can’t compromise the tuition fees. So we at Yocket help you with that! d. Evaluate every loan as an option that fits in your overall plan - There are many loan options available in the market, you just have to compare among the best options. We at Yocket can help you not just with Education Loans but also with Financial Counselling related to your Study Financial requirements.Good Luck! MBBS and MD are two different courses. One is a bachelor’s course while other is for masters. If you are opting for an education loan, then you need to apply for both these courses separately. However, if it is an integrated course in medicine which you wish to pursue then you can apply for it using a single loan application. In short, you can apply for just one course at a time. On the other hand, if there are two separate courses which you wish to pursue at the same time, then instead of opting for an education loan, you should opt for a loan which gives you the freedom of end usage. In order words, a loan which gives you the liberty of using it for any purpose you feel like. Two loan options which are very popular in this category include personal loans and loan against property. To opt for a loan against the property you must ensure that you have an asset which you can pledge an asset to the lender and in the absence of which your loan application will be rejected. Thus, if you do not have any asset to offer, I suggest that you instead opt for a personal loan. There are a number of lenders including financial institutions which offer personal loan for higher education at very competitive interest rates. The loan amount is high and the best part is that you get to choose the repayment tenor as per your preference. This ensures that repaying back the loan amount does not become a burden. I hope this helps. Thanks for A2A! The answer is big No. It is nothing but a financial blunder to invest 50 lakh for MBBS by taking a student loan. I don’t know whether you will be able to recover it or not but the cautious word beforehand is don't take a student loan for studying MBBS. In case you have 50 lakhs with you and want to be a doctor, you can consider MBBS but not with the loan. Let me explain you the financial aspect of it in a bit details. For the sake of simplification, I am assuming that you will be paying tuition fees of 10 lakh each year for 5 years and you will start repaying the tuition fees a year after that. The rate of interest ranges between 8–14% for education loan. I am keeping it 10% for the ease of calculation. 1st Year Tuition Fees: 10,00,000 2nd Year Tuition Fees: 10,00,000 + 10% interest + 1000000 = 2100000 3rd Year Tuition Fees: 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 = 3310000 4th Year Tuition Fees: 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 = 4641000 5th Year Tuition Fees: 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% = 6105100 6th Year Interest: 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 1000000 + 10% + 10% = 6715610 Once you start paying your 50 lac after the 6th year, you will have to pay 6715610. You have below-mentioned options to pay back your loan depending on the duration. 5 Year EMI Plan: Impossible to pay the EMI  10 Year EMI Plan: Impossible to pay the EMI  15 Year EMI Plan:  20 Year EMI Plan:  You will have to pay 65000 each month for 20 years to pay back your education loan. You will be in no position to do your post-graduation. Read here about a doctor's salary, Waseem Siddiqui's answer to What is the salary of a doctor in India? Cheers!",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:46:11.250Z"),
    "question" : "Is it worth doing an MBBS in a self-finance college with an education loan? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

