    "answer" : "In my honest opinion, it is beneficial to take out an education loan. Sometimes, people apply for education loans as a back up option/contingency plan. Rest, it depends upon your needs and requirements. If your target college/course is expensive or you are looking to apply to foreign university then education loan is the only option for you. You could also apply for scholarships or financial aid from the college you want to attend. Before you go ahead with an education loan from a certain institute, consider these factors - Loan amount required and the loan amount the bank can sanctionSecured loan or unsecured loan, that is if you can pledge collateral or notIn case of secured loan then the value of the collateral should be enough to cover the loan amount requiredRate of interest - compare ROIs of different banks to get the best deal.Moratorium periodLoan tenureExpenses coveredThere are many loan options available in the market and the schemes differ according to the needs of the applicant. If you are looking for an education loan to finance your study abroad then I would advice you to look at SBI’s Global Ed-Vantage Scheme. SBI provides one of the lowest rate of interest in the market, that is 9.75% for men and 9.25% for women. Plus, they provide fixed ROI whereas all other banks provide floating rate of interest. Loan amount ranges from INR 20 lakhs to INR 1.5 crore. Usually, SBI sanctions loan in 30 days, so I ’d suggest you to apply for a loan via GyanDhan as we have partnered with major lenders in the market and we can get it done in 12 to 15 days. We have experience with foreign education loan and have helped quite a lot of students. With GyanDhan, your bank visits will reduce to 1 or 2. We provide a customized document checklist, and document pickup service in major cities. Request for a callback. Moreover, Gyandhan’s services is free of cost as we get the money from the bank. Read about SBI’s Global Ed-Vantage Scheme here There are many other