    "job_link" : "https://www.quora.com/Does-ICICI-Bank-finance-an-education-loan-for-KIIT?-",
    "answer" : "Education loan is applied by almost all students aspiring to go different countries to do their Masters. Let me explain the process and struggle I faced during this COVID situation to get my education loan sanctioned. After getting the offer letter from Saint Mary’s University, Halifax, Canada for my Masters in Data Analytics & Computing, I was filled with joy and also thought about rest of the process to get my Visa done. I started searching for banks from March 2020 with lesser rate of interest ( which I think is important) and have gone through bank portals of almost all banks in India. What I could find is except 3 to 4 small banks, every bank has the loan margin amount which I needed. I initially thought of HDFC Credila and ICICI as well, but seeing their RoI, I was in a dilemma of going to it or not. I know if I did go through anyone of them, by this time I would have Visa in my hand. But, as my University postponed the course to January 2021, I thought I had so much of time to search other banks as well. Then came to my mind is Bank of Baroda with lesser rate of interest. I went to the nearest branch of BoB and asked the process of applying education loan in that bank ( I actually went through the bank loan portal and all things on my own by that time). The process was very clear and the documents which you need to submit will be handy if you have a flat/house to keep as collateral. I filled the application form and submitted all the documents to the bank. The process was quite fast and within less time, legal opinion by advocate and legal valuation of the property is done. While I was waiting for Mortgage registration process, one day I got a call from BoB saying that my loan got cancelled as Pre-Visa disbursement is not happening in COVID time for non-premier institutes of BoB. This was a big shock to me and I couldn’t come out of that for 1 week. The thought of re-applying in other bank with lesser RoI and the process is tough. One of my friends in same cohort of SMU (Hem Sai Charan) suggested me to talk with WeMakeScholars once on this issue. Then I immediately approached them in no time and explained everything that happened to me with Bank of Baroda. Meanwhile as I got news that SMU is conducting online classes in January, I deferred my admission to September 2021 as I am LASIK operated. I need to thank Ms. Prathyusha from WeMakeScholars in understanding my issue and solving the problem. After WeMakeScholars and BoB talked on this issue, they asked me one thing. The assurance from University that, if Visa gets cancelled then the money paid to University need to be returned from University, which luckily I got it from SMU. I submitted the assurance and again re-applied the loan from Bank of Baroda via WeMakeScholars this time. This time the process was much smoother as already legal opinion and legal valuation is already done. I also need to thank Durga and Anand from Bank of Baroda SMS team, in processing my documents and the process. Due to the COVID time, the process was somewhat slow but Bank of Baroda is such a good bank to apply loans. Two days back, I got my Loan Sanction Letter and I am looking forward for disbursement and Visa process. Generally, education loans are offered in specific slabs: a) Below Rs. 4 lakhs, b) Between Rs. 4 lakhs and Rs. 7.5 lakhs and c) Above Rs. 7.5 lakhs. Overview While availing any kind of loan, the most important aspect that has to be considered by the borrower is the interest rate offered by the chosen bank. The interest rate for any type of education loan differs according to the loan amount availed, the loan tenure, educational institution chosen and can be a fixed or floating rate. The interest payment for an education loan varies depending on the borrower. Interest rate payments are generally done immediately after the loan disbursal. Most banks offer a moratorium period after the sanction of the loan, during which the borrower does not have to repay the principal portion of the education loan. The scheduled repayment can start after this period, which is generally after the completion of the course. But borrowers can also pay the interest beforehand during the time of disbursal to avoid the burden of repaying higher amounts later. Another key point to be considered while looking into the interest rate given by any lender is whether the bank is calculating the interest on a quarterly reducing balance basis or on a daily reducing balance basis. The Central Government provides a full Interest Rate Subsidy Scheme to the economically weaker segments of the society, during the moratorium period of the education loan. Some banks also provide concessions for women applicants and offer a slightly lower interest rate. Comparison of different Bank Interest Rates Axis Bank  Up to Rs. 4 Lakhs (15.20%)  Loans greater than Rs. 4 Lakhs and upto Rs. 7.5 Lakhs (14.70%)  Loans greater than Rs. 7.5 Lakhs (13.70%) Bank of Baroda For all loan types and amounts (8.50%) onwards Canara Bank For Vidhya Turant Loan Scheme (6.60%)  Up to Rs. 4 Lakhs (10.40%)  Rs. 4 Lakhs to Rs. 7.50 Lakhs (10.40%) Loans above Rs. 7.50 lakhs (10.20%)  IBA´s Model Loan scheme for Vocational Education & Training (9.90%) HDFC Bank Minimum APR (9.00%)  Maximum APR (13.86%)  Average APR (11.57%) Kotak Mahindra Bank For all loan types and amounts (11.5% to 24%) Punjab National Bank PNB Kaushal (8.55% onwards)  PNB Saraswati/Udaan (10.30% onwards)  PNB Pratibha (for admission to IITs , IIMs and XLRI Jamshedpur) (8.45% onwards)  PNB Pratibha (for admission to other colleges) (8.55% onwards)  PNB Honhaar (10.45%) State Bank of India Up to Rs. 7.5 Lakhs (10.25%)  Above Rs. 7.5 Lakhs (10.50%) Avanse For all loan types and amounts (10% to 16.50%) Credila For all loan types and amounts (11.85%) onwards As on 04/03/2020 Note : As many of the PSBs have been merged i have removed few of the entries permanently and kept only top players in the field. There are other things too like processing fees, moratorium period and margins, check them out too. Thank you. Hope it would help. For any loan, interest has to be paid. The moratorium is only for repayment of the loan during the course period or until you secure a job whichever is later (because you do not have source of income, as a student). Simple interest is charged on Education loan during the moratorium period and once the repayment period starts, the interest is compounded, like any other loan. Pl verify whether the Bank has granted/classified your loan as Education loan, first.",
    "date" : ISODate("2021-02-25T06:51:19.579Z"),
    "question" : "Does ICICI Bank finance an education loan for KIIT? ",
    "source" : "Quora"
}

